       │ search results
       ▼
┌───────────────────────┐
│ Flask API /search     │
│ /suggest /semantic     │
└────────┬──────────────┘
         │ JSON
         ▼
┌────────────────────────┐
│ React Frontend (UI)    │
│ Autocomplete + Cards   │
└────────────────────────┘

🧪 Example Query Response
{
  "query": "national anthem",
  "results": [
    {
      "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jana_Gana_Mana",
      "title": "Jana Gana Mana - Wikipedia",
      "snippet": "National anthem of India ...",
      "score": 0.0318
    }
  ]
}

🧭 Setup Guide (Local)
1️⃣ Backend
cd Search_engine
pip install -r requirements.txt
python api/server.py

2️⃣ Frontend
cd search-ui
npm install
npm start

🧑‍💻 How It Works Internally

Crawls pages & extracts text

Builds inverted index {term: {doc: count}}

Computes TF-IDF (term_frequency / doc_length) * log(total/docs_with_term)

Computes semantic cosine similarity

Returns sorted results combined

React fetches & displays cards + autocomplete

🎤 Interview Pitch (use this)

I built a fully functional search engine from scratch using Python and React.
It uses a custom web crawler, an inverted index, TF-IDF scoring, semantic search using MiniLM,
and autocomplete via Trie. I deployed the backend on Render and the frontend on Vercel.
This project demonstrates search infrastructure design similar to real search engines like Google.

